         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>The Temple of Zeus was built in the second century B.C., and reconstructed after the Jewish revolt. Ensoli, art. cit.,
               suggests that this text came from the adjacent arch, and was later re-used in the Temple </p>
            <p> The reading is taken from the photograph since some letters on the edge of the crack are now missing. </p>
            <p> C.E. 138 between 25th Feb., when Hadrian adopted Antoninus, and 10th July, when he died. </p>

            <p> line 7: for the phrase, cf. Syll. 326, line 15, κεκοσμημένην τὴν [πόλιν...] at      in 307/6 B.C. and Syll3. 1100, line 21, τόν τε νεὼ τοῦ θεοῦ κατεσκεύασεν καὶ ἐκόσμησεν πολλοῖς [καὶ καλοῖ ἀνα]θήμασιν at Piraeus in 185-4 B.C.
               Most commentators have believed that the reference was to the statues on this base; a colossal Zeus Aegiochus perhaps, 
               but by no means certainly an Athena and Hera; Eagnani argued that it was a restoration of cult statues throughout the city. 
               Applebaum clearly took it in the same sense, since he regards the text as evidence that the Jewish rebels in C.E. 115 
               carried out a particularly extensive destruction of cult statues, also explaining the adjective ἀνόσιοι applied to them in the literary account 
               of the revolt. The wording points clearly to imperial benefactions throughout the city. it is unnecessary to regard all these as restoration 
               of damage done in the Jewish revolt.</p>
         </div>
         
